Based on a comprehensive review of the WARDEN documentation and a deep dive into the project's source code, I have audited the 6 requested components of the WARDEN ecosystem.

Below is an extremely detailed breakdown of errors, architectural problems, deviations from the documentation, and the current working condition of each part of the project.

1) Backend (Python / FastAPI)
Current State: Structurally solid and capable of routing WebSocket connections, but severely lacking in data persistence and AI RAG implementation.

🚨 Errors & Problems:

Disabled Database Persistence: According to Schema.md and TRD.md, Firebase/Firestore is supposed to handle persistent data (Users, Incidents, Tasks). However, in services/db_service.py, Firebase has been entirely disabled (db = None) due to an invalid_grant credential error. All database interactions are mocked and print to the console instead of saving.
Missing Vector Database (RAG Pipeline): Implementation.md and TRD.md explicitly define a vectorDB_service.py to power the AI reasoning relay. This entire feature is missing from the codebase.
Hardcoded "Master" Overrides (Security Vulnerability): In api/guest_routes.py, there is a hardcoded master override that allows anyone to bypass OTP verification by passing 000000. If this is deployed, it represents a critical security flaw.
Faked Threat Verification: The /verify-threat and /api/analyze endpoints (in api/routes.py) completely mock the computer vision verification, returning hardcoded confidence: 1.0 instead of actually running any analysis.
2) Responder Desktop App (Rust / Tauri & React)
Current State: The React frontend logic is well-built, but the Rust/Tauri backend will fail immediately upon attempting to launch the local AI sidecar.

🚨 Errors & Problems:

Missing Executable (llama-server.exe): The Rust setup function in src-tauri/src/main.rs explicitly attempts to spawn binaries/llama-server.exe to run the Gemma AI model offline. However, this executable does not exist in the repository.
Fragmented AI Model: The Gemma AI model (gemma-4-e2b.gguf) is split into multiple .part files (likely due to GitHub size limits) inside the binaries folder. The Tauri app expects a unified .gguf file and will panic because the joined file isn't present by default. (Note: Users must manually run the rejoin_model.ps1 script found in the root directory to fix this, but it still won't resolve the missing executable).
3) Simulation Engine (Node.js / Turborepo)
Current State: Highly advanced, seemingly fully functional, and well-architected.

🚨 Errors & Problems:

Violation of Local-First Rules: Rules.md (Rule 3) explicitly dictates prioritizing local deployments over cloud defaults. However, in apps/api/src/server.ts (around line 301), the simulation engine hardcodes the backend URL to a Google Cloud Run instance (warden-backend-774533752332.us-central1.run.app) if BACKEND_URL is not defined in an environment variable.
Monolithic Controller: server.ts is over 900 lines long. It handles everything from Express routing and WebSocket event emitting, to Cellular Automata grid logic and manual incident injection. This should ideally be refactored into modular controller files.
4) Staff Desktop App (Rust / Tauri & React)
Current State: Similar to the Responder app, the frontend is functional but the Rust backend shares the exact same critical failures.

🚨 Errors & Problems:

AI Sidecar Boot Failure: Just like the Responder app, src-tauri/src/main.rs relies on llama-server.exe and an unmerged gemma-4-e2b.gguf file. Booting this Tauri app will result in the AI model silently failing to launch in the background.
5) Warden Android App (Android / Kotlin Compose)
Current State: Beautifully structured modern Android application using Jetpack Compose and Kotlin Coroutines.

🚨 Errors & Problems:

Hardcoded Cloud Endpoints: In com.jdcoders.crisisconnect.services.ApiConfig, the BASE_URL is hardcoded to https://warden-backend-774533752332.us-central1.run.app. Because the backend is intended to be run as a standalone local service during development (as per Rules.md), the Android app will fail to communicate with your local backend unless this is manually changed to your machine's local IP or 10.0.2.2 (for Emulators).
6) Website (Vite / React / Tailwind)
Current State: A functional frontend scaffolding.

🚨 Errors & Problems:

Undocumented Component: This Website directory is not mentioned anywhere in the PRD.md, TRD.md, or Implementation.md. It is a barebones React 19 project using Vite and Tailwind 4. It builds successfully, but its purpose within the ecosystem is currently undefined in the documentation.